## Superseded from cross-doc-citation-drift-defenses

```yaml
name: cross-doc-citation-drift-defenses
description: Procedural and audit defenses against section-numbering drift and
  arXiv ID-to-title swaps in inter-citing markdown corpora.
category: documentation
date: 2026-05-12
version: "1.0.0"
user-invocable: false
verification: verified-local
tags: [citation, cross-reference, section-numbering, stale-reference, arxiv,
  primary-source, authoring-discipline, multi-document-corpus, citation-drift,
  reorganization-discipline]
```

Two failure modes covered:

A) Section-numbering drift: when doc Y is reorganized but its citers (doc X) are not
   updated. Defense A.1: global mapping table at moment of reorganization, applied via
   global find-replace in one commit. Defense A.2: use `§` glyph prefix in headings
   (grep-auditable). Defense A.3: cross-corpus reviewer subagent.

B) arXiv ID-to-title swap in multi-author corpora: survives multiple per-file review
   cycles because each entry looks plausible in isolation. Defense B.1: WebFetch every
   arXiv ID against abs page during initial drafting. Defense B.2: full titles in every
   citation entry (no genre-tag shorthand as locator). Defense B.3: `[ASSUMPTION — to
   validate]` marker for borderline citations. Defense B.4: both procedural AND
   verification-based defenses (not either alone).

Failed: 8 stale §-references (§6.x.x dangling after ALGORITHM flattened to §1-§7);
2 arXiv-ID-to-title swaps in Millidge PC paper corpus survived two prior reviewer cycles;
genre-tag shorthand made swaps invisible; pattern scrubs cannot detect structural drift.

Verified on: mvillmow/Random — Predictive-Coding-in-Mojo Phase 0.

